obj_root_law_sections_8_content:
  string
  line 8
  line `( b ) foreign currency account held or operated by such person or class of persons and the limit up`
  line `to which the Reserve Bank may specify;`
  line `( c ) foreign exchange acquired or received before the 8th day of July, 1947 or any income arising`
  line `or accruing thereon which is held outside India by any person in pursuance of a general or special`
  line `permission granted by the Reserve Bank;`
  line `( d ) foreign exchange held by a person resident in India up to such limit as the Reserve Bank may`
  line `specify, if such foreign exchange was acquired by way of gift or inheritance from a person referred to`
  line `in clause ( c ), including any income arising therefrom;`
  line `( e ) foreign exchange acquired from employment, business, trade, vocation, services, honorarium,`
  line `gifts, inheritance or any other legitimate means up to such limit as the Reserve Bank may specify; and`
  line `( f ) such other receipts in foreign exchange as the Reserve Bank may specify.`
  line `CHAPTER III`
  line `A UTHORISED PERSON`
  line `10. Authorised person. — ( 1 ) The Reserve Bank may, on an application made to it in this behalf,`
  line `authorise any person to be known as authorised person to deal in foreign exchange or in foreign`
  line `securities, as an authorised dealer, money changer or off-shore banking unit or in any other manner as it`
  line `deems fit.`
  line `( 2 ) An authorisation under this section shall be in writing and shall be subject to the conditions laid`
  line `down therein.`
  line `( 3 ) An authorisation granted under sub-section ( 1 ) may be revoked by the Reserve Bank at any time if`
  line `the Reserve Bank is satisfied that —`
  line `( a ) it is in public interest so to do; or`
  line `( b ) the authorised person has failed to comply with the condition subject to which the`
  line `authorisation was granted or has contravened any of the provisions of the Act or any rule, regulation,`
  line `notification, direction or order made thereunder:`
  line `Provided that no such authorisation shall be revoked on any ground referred to in clause ( b ) unless the`
  line `authorised person has been given a reasonable opportunity of making a representation in the matter.`
  line `( 4 ) An authorised person shall, in all his dealings in foreign exchange or foreign security, comply`
  line `with such general or special directions or orders as the Reserve Bank may, from time to time, think fit to`
  line `give, and, except with the previous permission of the Reserve Bank, an authorised person shall not engage`
  line `in any transaction involving any foreign exchange or foreign security which is not in conformity with the`
  line `terms of his authorisation under this section.`
  line `( 5 ) An authorised person shall, before undertaking any transaction in foreign exchange on behalf of`
  line `any person, require that person to make such declaration and to give such information as will reasonably`
  line `satisfy him that the transaction will not involve, and is not designed for the purpose of any contravention`
  line `or evasion of the provisions of this Act or of any rule, regulation, notification, direction or order made`
  line `thereunder, and where the said person refuses to comply with any such requirement or makes only`
  line `unsatisfactory compliance therewith, the authorised person shall refuse in writing to undertake the`
  line `transaction and shall, if he has reason to believe that any such contravention or evasion as aforesaid is`
  line `contemplated by the person, report the matter to the Reserve Bank.`
  line `( 6 ) Any person, other than an authorised person, who has acquired or purchased foreign exchange for`
  line `any purpose mentioned in the declaration made by him to authorised person under sub-section ( 5 ) does`
  line `not use it for such purpose or does not surrender it to authorised person within the specified period or uses`
  line `the foreign exchange so acquired or purchased for any other purpose for which purchase or acquisition of`
  line `foreign exchange is not permissible under the provisions of the Act or the rules or regulations or direction`
obj_root_law_sections_8_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_9:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-9
  sectionNo (9)
  orderNo 9
  title `Page 9`
  content obj_root_law_sections_9_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_9_footnotes
  sourcePage 9
obj_root_law_sections_9_content:
  string
  line 9
  line `or order made thereunder shall be deemed to have committed contravention of the provisions of the Act`
  line `for the purpose of this section.`
  line `11. Reserve Bank’ s powers to issue directions to authorised person. — ( 1 ) The Reserve Bank may,`
  line `for the purpose of securing compliance with the provisions of this Act and of any rules, regulations,`
  line `notifications or directions made thereunder, give to the authorised persons any direction in regard to`
  line `making of payment or the doing or desist from doing any act relating to foreign exchange or foreign`
  line security.
  line `( 2 ) The Reserve Bank may, for the purpose of ensuring the compliance with the provisions of this Act`
  line `or of any rule, regulation, notification, direction or order made thereunder, direct any authorised person to`
  line `furnish such information, in such manner, as it deems fit.`
  line `( 3 ) Where any authorised person contravenes any direction given by the Reserve Bank under this Act`
  line `or fails to file any return as directed by the Reserve Bank, the Reserve Bank may, after giving reasonable`
  line `opportunity of being heard, impose on the authorised person a penalty which may extend to ten thousand`
  line `rupees and in the case of continuing contravention with an additional penalty which may extend to two`
  line `thousand rupees for every day during which such contravention continues.`
  line `12. Power of Reserve Bank to inspect authorised person. — ( 1 ) The Reserve Bank may, at any`
  line `time, cause an inspection to be made, by any officer of the Reserve Bank specially authorised in writing`
  line `by the Reserve Bank in this behalf, of the business of any authorised person as may appear to it to be`
  line `necessary or expedient for the purpose of —`
  line `( a ) verifying the correctness of any statement, information or particulars furnished to the Reserve`
  line Bank;
  line `( b ) obtaining any information or particulars which such authorised person has failed to furnish on`
  line `being called upon to do so;`
  line `( c ) securing compliance with the provisions of this Act or of any rules, regulations, directions or`
  line `orders made thereunder.`
  line `( 2 ) It shall be the duty of every authorised person, and where such person is a company or a firm,`
  line `every director, partner or other officer of such company or firm, as the case may be, to produce to any`
  line `officer making an inspection under sub-section ( 1 ), such books, accounts and other documents in his`
  line `custody or power and to furnish any statement or information relating to the affairs of such person,`
  line `company or firm as the said officer may require within such time and in such manner as the said officer`
  line `may direct.`
  line `CHAPTER IV`
  line `C ONTRAVENTION AND PENALTIES`
  line `13. Penalties. — ( 1 ) If any person contravenes any provision of this Act, or contravenes any rule,`
  line `regulation, notification, direction or order issued in exercise of the powers under this Act, or contravenes`
  line `any condition subject to which an authorisation is issued by the Reserve Bank, he shall, upon`
  line `adjudication, be liable to a penalty up to thrice the sum involved in such contravention where such`
  line `amount is quantifiable, or up to two lakh rupees where the amount is not quantifiable, and where such`
  line `contravention is a continuing one, further penalty which may extend to five thousand rupees for every day`
  line `after the first day during which the contravention continues.`
  line `1 [( 1A ) If any person is found to have acquired any foreign exchange, foreign security or immovable`
  line `property, situated outside India, of the aggregate value exceeding the threshold prescribed under the`
  line `proviso to sub-section ( 1 ) of section 37A, he shall be liable to a penalty up to three times the sum`
  line `involved in such contravention and confiscation of the value equivalent, situated in India, the Foreign`
  line `exchange, foreign security or immovable property.`
  line `1. Ins. by Act 20 of 2015, s. 140 (w.e.f. 9-9-2015).`
obj_root_law_sections_9_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_10:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-10
  sectionNo (10)
  orderNo 10
  title `Page 10`
  content obj_root_law_sections_10_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_10_footnotes
  sourcePage 10
obj_root_law_sections_10_content:
  string
  line 10
  line `( 1B ) If the Adjudicating Authority, in a proceeding under sub-section ( 1A ) deems fits, he may, after`
  line `recording the reasons in writing, recommend for the initiation of prosecution and if the Director of`
  line `Enforcement is satisfied, he may, after recording the reasons in writing, may direct prosecution by filing a`
  line `Criminal Complaint against the guilty person by an officer not below the rank of Assistant Director.`
  line `( 1C ) If any person is found to have acquired any foreign exchange, foreign security or immovable`
  line `property, situated outside India, of the aggregate value exceeding the threshold prescribed under the`
  line `proviso to sub-section ( 1 ) of section 37A, he shall be, in addition to the penalty imposed under`
  line `sub-section ( 1A ), punishable with imprisonment for a term which may extend to five years and with fine.`
  line `( 1D ) No court shall take cognizance of an offence under sub-section ( 1C ) of section 13 except as on`
  line `complaint in writing by an officer not below the rank of Assistant Director referred to in`
  line `sub-section ( 1B ).]`
  line `( 2 ) Any Adjudicating Authority adjudging any contravention under sub-section ( 1 ), may, if he thinks`
  line `fit in addition to any penalty which he may impose for such contravention direct that any currency,`
  line `security or any other money or property in respect of which the contravention has taken place shall be`
  line `confiscated to the Central Government and further direct that the foreign exchange holdings, if any, of the`
  line `persons committing the contraventions or any part thereof, shall be brought back into India or shall be`
  line `retained outside India in accordance with the directions made in this behalf.`
  line `Explanation. — For the purposes of this sub-section, “ property ” in respect of which contravention has`
  line `taken place, shall include —`
  line `( a ) deposits in a bank, where the said property is converted into such deposits;`
  line `( b ) Indian currency, where the said property is converted into that currency; and`
  line `( c ) any other property which has resulted out of the conversion of that property.`
  line `14. Enforcement of the orders of Adjudicating Authority. — ( 1 ) Subject to the provisions of`
  line `sub-section ( 2 ) of section 19, if any person fails to make full payment of the penalty imposed on him`
  line `under section 13 within a period of ninety days from the date on which the notice for payment of such`
  line `penalty is served on him, he shall be liable to civil imprisonment under this section.`
  line `( 2 ) No order for the arrest and detention in civil prison of a defaulter shall be made unless the`
  line `Adjudicating Authority has issued and served a notice upon the defaulter calling upon him to appear`
  line `before him on the date specified in the notice and to show cause why he should not be committed to the`
  line `civil prison, and unless the Adjudicating Authority, for reasons in writing, is satisfied —`
  line `( a ) that the defaulter, with the object or effect of obstructing the recovery of penalty, has after the`
  line `issue of notice by the Adjudicating Authority, dishonestly transferred, concealed, or removed any part`
  line `of his property, or`
  line `( b ) that the defaulter has, or has had since the issuing of notice by the Adjudicating Authority, the`
  line `means to pay the arrears or some substantial part thereof and refuses or neglects or has refused or`
  line `neglected to pay the same.`
  line `( 3 ) Notwithstanding anything contained in sub-section ( 1 ), a warrant for the arrest of the defaulter`
  line `may be issued by the Adjudicating Authority if the Adjudicating Authority is satisfied, by affidavit or`
  line `otherwise, that with the object or effect of delaying the execution of the certificate the defaulter is likely`
  line `to abscond or leave the local limits of the jurisdiction of the Adjudicating Authority.`
  line `( 4 ) Where appearance is not made pursuant to a notice issued and served under sub-section ( 1 ), the`
  line `Adjudicating Authority may issue a warrant for the arrest of the defaulter.`
  line `( 5 ) A warrant of arrest issued by the Adjudicating Authority under sub-section ( 3 ) or sub-section ( 4 )`
  line `may also be executed by any other Adjudicating Authority within whose jurisdiction the defaulter may for`
  line `the time being be found.`
  line `( 6 ) Every person arrested in pursuance of a warrant of arrest under this section shall be brought`
  line `before the Adjudicating Authority issuing the warrant as soon as practicable and in any event within`
  line `twenty-four hours of his arrest (exclusive of the time required for the journey):`
obj_root_law_sections_10_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_11:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-11
  sectionNo (11)
  orderNo 11
  title `Page 11`
  content obj_root_law_sections_11_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_11_footnotes
  sourcePage 11
obj_root_law_sections_11_content:
  string
  line 11
  line `Provided that, if the defaulter pays the amount entered in the warrant of arrest as due and the costs of`
  line `the arrest to the officer arresting him, such officer shall at once release him.`
  line `Explanation. — For the purposes of this sub-section, where the defaulter is a Hindu undivided family,`
  line `the karta thereof shall be deemed to be the defaulter.`
  line `( 7 ) When a defaulter appears before the Adjudicating Authority pursuant to a notice to show cause or`
  line `is brought before the Adjudicating Authority under this section, the Adjudicating Authority shall give the`
  line `defaulter an opportunity showing cause why he should not be committed to the civil prison.`
  line `( 8 ) Pending the conclusion of the inquiry, the Adjudicating Authority may, in his discretion, order the`
  line `defaulter to be detained in the custody of such officer as the Adjudicating Authority may think fit or`
  line `release him on his furnishing the security to the satisfaction of the Adjudicating Authority for his`
  line `appearance as and when required.`
  line `( 9 ) Upon the conclusion of the inquiry, the Adjudicating Authority may make an order for the`
  line `detention of the defaulter in the civil prison and shall in that event cause him to be arrested if he is not`
  line `already under arrest:`
  line `Provided that in order to give a defaulter an opportunity of satisfying the arrears, the Adjudicating`
  line `Authority may, before making the order of detention, leave the defaulter in the custody of the officer`
  line `arresting him or of any other officer for a specified period not exceeding fifteen days, or release him on`
  line `his furnishing security to the satisfaction of the Adjudicating Authority for his appearance at the`
  line `expiration of the specified period if the arrears are not satisfied.`
  line `( 10 ) When the Adjudicating Authority does not make an order of detention under sub-section ( 9 ), he`
  line `shall, if the defaulter is under arrest, direct his release.`
  line `( 11 ) Every person detained in the civil prison in execution of the certificate may be so detained, —`
  line `( a ) where the certificate is for a demand of an amount exceeding rupees one crore, up to three`
  line `years, and`
  line `( b ) in any other case, up to six months:`
  line `Provided that he shall be released from such detention on the amount mentioned in the warrant for his`
  line `detention being paid to the officer-in-charge of the civil prison.`
  line `( 12 ) A defaulter released from detention under this section shall not, merely by reason of his release,`
  line `be discharged from his liability for the arrears, but he shall not be liable to be arrested under the`
  line `certificate in execution of which he was detained in the civil prison.`
  line `( 13 ) A detention order may be executed at any place in India in the manner provided for the execution`
  line `of warrant of arrest under the Code of Criminal Procedure, 1973 (2 of 1974).`
  line `1 [14A. Power of recover arrears of penalty. — ( 1 ) Save as otherwise provided in this Act, the`
  line `Adjudicating Authority may, by order in writing, authorise an officer of Enforcement not below the rank`
  line `of Assistant Director to recover any arrears of penalty from any person who fails to make full payment of`
  line `penalty imposed on him under section 13 within the period of ninety days from the date on which the`
  line `notice for payment of such penalty is served on him.`
  line `( 2 ) The officer referred to in sub-section ( 1 ) shall exercise all the like powers which are conferred on`
  line `the income-tax authority in relation to recovery of tax under the Income-tax Act, 1961 (43 of 1961) and`
  line `the procedure laid down under the Second Schedule to the said Act shall mutatis mutandis apply in`
  line `relation to recovery of arrears of penalty under this Act.]`
  line `15. Power to compound contravention. — ( 1 ) Any contravention under section 13 may, on an`
  line `application made by the person committing such contravention, be compounded within one hundred and`
  line `eighty days from the date of receipt of application by the Director of Enforcement or such other officers`
  line `of the Directorate of Enforcement and officers of the Reserve Bank as may be authorised in this behalf by`
  line `the Central Government in such manner as may be prescribed.`
  line `1. Section 14A shall stand inserted (date to be notified) by Act 28 of 2016, s. 229.`
obj_root_law_sections_11_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_12:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-12
  sectionNo (12)
  orderNo 12
  title `Page 12`
  content obj_root_law_sections_12_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_12_footnotes
  sourcePage 12
obj_root_law_sections_12_content:
  string
  line 12
  line `( 2 ) Where a contravention has been compounded under sub-section ( 1 ), no proceeding or further`
  line `proceeding, as the case may be, shall be initiated or continued, as the case may be, against the person`
  line `committing such contravention under that section, in respect of the contravention so compounded.`
  line `CHAPTER V`
  line `A DJUDICATION AND APPEAL`
  line `16. Appointment of Adjudicating Authority. — ( 1 ) For the purpose of adjudication under`
  line `section 13, the Central Government may, by an order published in the Official Gazette, appoint as many`
  line `officers of the Central Government as it may think fit, as the Adjudicating Authorities for holding an`
  line `inquiry in the manner prescribed after giving the person alleged to have committed contravention under`
  line `section 13, against whom a complaint has been made under sub-section ( 3 ) (hereinafter in this section`
  line `referred to as the said person) a reasonable opportunity of being heard for the purpose of imposing any`
  line `penalty:`
  line `Provided that where the Adjudicating Authority is of opinion that the said person is likely to abscond`
  line `or is likely to evade in any manner, the payment of penalty, if levied, it may direct the said person to`
  line `furnish a bond or guarantee for such amount and subject to such conditions as it may deem fit.`
  line `( 2 ) The Central Government shall, while appointing the Adjudicating Authorities under`
  line `sub-section ( 1 ), also specify in the order published in the Official Gazette, their respective jurisdictions.`
  line `( 3 ) No Adjudicating Authority shall hold an enquiry under sub-section ( 1 ) except upon a complaint in`
  line `writing made by any officer authorised by a general or special order by the Central Government.`
  line `( 4 ) The said person may appear either in person or take the assistance of a legal practitioner or a`
  line `chartered accountant of his choice for presenting his case before the Adjudicating Authority.`
  line `( 5 ) Every Adjudicating Authority shall have the same powers of a civil court which are conferred on`
  line `the Appellate Tribunal under sub-section ( 2 ) of section 28 and —`
  line `( a ) all proceedings before it shall be deemed to be judicial proceedings within the meaning of`
  line `sections 193 and 228 of the Indian Penal Code (45 of 1860);`
  line `( b ) shall be deemed to be a civil court for the purposes of sections 345 and 346 of the Code of`
  line `Criminal Procedure, 1973 (2 of 1974).`
  line `( 6 ) Every Adjudicating Authority shall deal with the complaint under sub-section ( 2 ) as expeditiously`
  line `as possible and endeavour shall be made to dispose of the complaint finally within one year from the date`
  line `of receipt of the complaint:`
  line `Provided that where the complaint cannot be disposed of within the said period, the Adjudicating`
  line `Authority shall record periodically the reasons in writing for not disposing of the complaint within the`
  line `said period.`
  line `17. Appeal to Special Director (Appeals). — ( 1 ) The Central Government shall, by notification,`
  line `appoint one or more Special Directors (Appeals) to hear appeals against the orders of the Adjudicating`
  line `Authorities under this section and shall also specify in the said notification the matter and places in`
  line `relation to which the Special Director (Appeals) may exercise jurisdiction.`
  line `( 2 ) Any person aggrieved by an order made by the Adjudicating Authority, being an Assistant`
  line `Director of Enforcement or a Deputy Director of Enforcement, may prefer an appeal to the Special`
  line `Director (Appeals).`
  line `( 3 ) Every appeal under sub-section ( 1 ) shall be filed within forty-five days from the date on which the`
  line `copy of the order made by the Adjudicating Authority is received by the aggrieved person and it shall be`
  line `in such form, verified in such manner and be accompanied by such fee as may be prescribed:`
  line `Provided that the Special Director (Appeals) may entertain an appeal after the expiry of the said`
  line `period of forty-five days, if he is satisfied that there was sufficient cause for not filing it within that`
  line period.
  line `( 4 ) On receipt of an appeal under sub-section ( 1 ), the Special Director (Appeals) may after giving the`
  line `parties to the appeal an opportunity of being heard, pass such order thereon as he thinks fit, confirming,`
  line `modifying or setting aside the order appealed against.`
obj_root_law_sections_12_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_13:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-13
  sectionNo (13)
  orderNo 13
  title `Page 13`
  content obj_root_law_sections_13_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_13_footnotes
  sourcePage 13
obj_root_law_sections_13_content:
  string
  line 13
  line `( 5 ) The Special Director (Appeals) shall send a copy of every order made by him to the parties to`
  line `appeal and to the concerned Adjudicating Authority.`
  line `( 6 ) The Special Director (Appeals) shall have the same powers of a civil court which are conferred on`
  line `the Appellate Tribunal under sub-section ( 2 ) of section 28 and —`
  line `( a ) all proceedings before him shall be deemed to be judicial proceedings within the meaning of`
  line `sections 193 and 228 of the Indian Penal Code (45 of 1860);`
  line `( b ) shall be deemed to be a civil court for the purposes of sections 345 and 346 of the Code of`
  line `Criminal Procedure, 1973 (2 of 1974).`
  line `1 [ 18. Appellate Tribunal. — The Appellate Tribunal constituted under sub-section ( 1 ) of section 12 of`
  line `the Smugglers and Foreign Exchange Manipulators (Forfeiture of Property) Act, 1976 (13 of 1976), shall,`
  line `on and from the commencement of Part XIV of Chapter VI of the Finance Act, 2017 (7 of 2017), be the`
  line `Appellate Tribunal for the purposes of this Act and the said Appellate Tribunal shall exercise the`
  line `jurisdiction, powers and authority conferred on it by or under this Act.]`
  line `19. Appeal to Appellate Tribunal — ( 1 ) Save as provided in sub-section ( 2 ), the Central Government`
  line `or any person aggrieved by an order made by an Adjudicating Authority, other than those referred to in`
  line `sub-section ( 1 ) of section 17, or the Special Director (Appeals), may prefer an appeal to the Appellate`
  line `Tribunal:`
  line `Provided that any person appealing against the order of the Adjudicating Authority or the Special`
  line `Director (Appeals) levying any penalty, shall while filing the appeal, deposit the amount of such penalty`
  line `with such authority as may be notified by the Central Government:`
  line `Provided further that where in any particular case, the Appellate Tribunal is of the opinion that the`
  line `deposit of such penalty would cause undue hardship to such person, the Appellate Tribunal may dispense`
  line `with such deposit subject to such conditions as it may deem fit to impose so as to safeguard the realisation`
  line `of penalty.`
  line `( 2 ) Every appeal under sub-section ( 1 ) shall be filed within a period of forty-five days from the date`
  line `on which a copy of the order made by the Adjudicating Authority or the Special Director (Appeals) is`
  line `received by the aggrieved person or by the Central Government and it shall be in such form, verified in`
  line `such manner and be accompanied by such fee as may be prescribed:`
  line `Provided that the Appellate Tribunal may entertain an appeal after the expiry of the said period of`
  line `forty-five days if it is satisfied that there was sufficient cause for not filing it within that period.`
  line `( 3 ) On receipt of an appeal under sub-section ( 1 ), the Appellate Tribunal may, after giving the parties`
  line `to the appeal an opportunity of being heard, pass such orders thereon as it thinks fit, confirming,`
  line `modifying or setting aside the order appealed against.`
  line `( 4 ) The Appellate Tribunal shall send a copy of every order made by it to the parties to the appeal and`
  line `to the concerned Adjudicating Authority or the Special Director (Appeals), as the case may be.`
  line `( 5 ) The appeal filed before the Appellate Tribunal under sub-section ( 1 ) shall be dealt with by it as`
  line `expeditiously as possible and endeavour shall be made by it to dispose of the appeal finally within one`
  line `hundred and eighty days from the date of receipt of the appeal:`
  line `Provided that where any appeal could not be disposed of within the said period of one hundred and`
  line `eighty days, the Appellate Tribunal shall record its reasons in writing for not disposing off the appeal`
  line `within the said period.`
  line `( 6 ) The Appellate Tribunal may, for the purpose of examining the legality, propriety or correctness of`
  line `any order made by the Adjudicating Authority under section 16 in relation to any proceeding, on its own`
  line `motion or otherwise, call for the records of such proceedings and make such order in the case as it thinks`
  line fit.
  line `20. [Composition of Appellate Tribunal.] Omitted by the finance Act, 2017 (7 of 2017), s. 165`
  line `( w.e.f. 26-5-2017).`
  line `1. Subs. by Act 7 of 2017, s. 165, for section 18 (w.e.f. 26-5-2017).`
obj_root_law_sections_13_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_14:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-14
  sectionNo (14)
  orderNo 14
  title `Page 14`
  content obj_root_law_sections_14_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_14_footnotes
  sourcePage 14
obj_root_law_sections_14_content:
  string
  line 14
  line `1 [ 21. Qualifications, for appointment of Special Director (Appeals). — A person shall not be`
  line `qualified for appointment as a Special Director (Appeals) unless he —`
  line `( a ) has been a member of the Indian Legal Service and has held a post in Grade I of that Service; or`
  line `( b ) has been a member of the Indian Revenue Service and has held a post equivalent to a Joint`
  line `Secretary to the Government of India.]`
  line `22. [Term of office.] Omitted by the Finance Act, 2017 (7 of 2017), s. 165 ( w.e.f. 26-5-2017).`
  line `2 [ 23. Terms and Condition of service of Special Director of (Appeals). — The salary and`
  line `allowances payable to and the other terms and conditions of service of the Special Director (Appeals)`
  line `shall be such as may be prescribed.]`
  line `24. [ Vacancies.] Omitted by the Finance Act, 2017 (7 of 2017), s. 165 ( w.e.f. 26-5-2017).`
  line `25. [ Resignation and removal.] Omitted by s. 165, ibid. ( w.e.f. 26-5-2017).`
  line `26. [ Member to act as Chairperson in certain circumstances.] Omitted by s. 165, ibid.`
  line `( w.e.f. 26-5-2017).`
  line `3 [ 27. Staff of Special Director (Appeal). — ( 1 ) The Central Government shall provide the office of`
  line `the Special Director (Appeals) with such officers and employees as it may deem fit.`
  line `( 2 ) The officers and employees of the office of the Special Director (Appeals) shall discharge their`
  line `functions under the general superintendence of the Special Director (Appeals).`
  line `( 3 ) The salaries and allowances and other terms and conditions of service of the officers and`
  line `employees of the office of the Special Director (Appeals) shall be such as may be prescribed.]`
  line `28. Procedure and powers of Appellate Tribunal and Special Director (Appeals). — ( 1 ) The`
  line `Appellate Tribunal and the Special Director (Appeals) shall not be bound by the procedure laid down by`
  line `the Code of Civil Procedure, 1908 (5 of 1908), but shall be guided by the principles of natural justice and,`
  line `subject to the other provisions of this Act, the Appellate Tribunal and the Special Director (Appeals) shall`
  line `have powers to regulate its own procedure.`
  line `( 2 ) The Appellate Tribunal and the Special Director (Appeals) shall have, for the purposes of`
  line `discharging its functions under this Act, the same powers as are vested in a civil court under the Code of`
  line `Civil Procedure, 1908 (5 of 1908), while trying a suit, in respect of the following matters, namely: —`
  line `( a ) summoning and enforcing the attendance of any person and examining him on oath;`
  line `( b ) requiring the discovery and production of documents;`
  line `( c ) receiving evidence on affidavits;`
  line `( d ) subject to the provisions of sections 123 and 124 of the Indian Evidence Act,`
  line `1872 (1 of 1872), requisitioning any public record or document or copy of such record or document`
  line `from any office;`
  line `( e ) issuing commissions for the examination of witnesses or documents;`
  line `( f ) reviewing its decisions;`
  line `( g ) dismissing a representation of default or deciding it ex parte;`
  line `( h ) setting aside any order of dismissal of any representation for default or any order passed by it`
  line `ex parte; and`
  line `( i ) any other matter which may be prescribed by the Central Government.`
  line `( 3 ) An order made by the Appellate Tribunal or the Special Director (Appeals) under this Act shall be`
  line `executable by the Appellate Tribunal or the Special Director (Appeals) as a decree of civil court and, for`
  line `1. Subs. by Act 7 of 2017, s. 165, for section 21 (w.e.f. 26-5-2017).`
  line `2. Subs. by s. 165, ibid., for section 23 (w.e.f. 26-5-2017).`
  line `3. Subs. by s. 165, ibid., for section 27 (w.e.f. 26-5-2017).`
obj_root_law_sections_14_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_15:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-15
  sectionNo (15)
  orderNo 15
  title `Page 15`
  content obj_root_law_sections_15_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_15_footnotes
  sourcePage 15
obj_root_law_sections_15_content:
  string
  line 15
  line `this purpose, the Appellate Tribunal and the Special Director (Appeals) shall have all the powers of a civil`
  line court.
  line `( 4 ) Notwithstanding anything contained in sub-section ( 3 ), the Appellate Tribunal or the Special`
  line `Director (Appeals) may transmit any order made by it to a civil court having local jurisdiction and such`
  line `civil court shall execute the order as if it were a decree made by that court.`
  line `( 5 ) All proceedings before the Appellate Tribunal and the Special Director (Appeals) shall be deemed`
  line `to be judicial proceedings within the meaning of sections 193 and 228 of the Indian`
  line `Penal Code (45 of 1860) and the Appellate Tribunal shall be deemed to be a civil court for the purposes`
  line `of sections 345 and 346 of the Code of Criminal Procedure, 1973 (2 of 1974).`
  line `29. [ Distribution of business amongst Benches.] Omitted by the Finance Act, 2017 (7 of 2017),`
  line `s. 165 ( w.e.f. 26-5-2017).`
  line `30. [ Power of Chairperson to transfer cases.] Omitted by s. 165, ibid. ( w.e.f. 26-5-2017).`
  line `31. [ Decision to be by majority.] Omitted by s. 165, ibid. ( w.e.f. 26-5-2017).`
  line `32. Right of appellant to take assistance of legal practitioner or chartered accountant and of`
  line `Government, to appoint presenting officers. — ( 1 ) A person preferring an appeal to the 1 [Special`
  line `Director (Appeals)] under this Act may either appear in person or take the assistance of a legal`
  line `practitioner or a chartered accountant of his choice to present his case before the 2 [Special Director`
  line `(Appeals)].`
  line `( 2 ) The Central Government may authorise one or more legal practitioners or chartered accountants`
  line `or any of its officers to act as presenting officers and every person so authorised may present the case`
  line `with respect to any appeal before the 2 [Special Director (Appeals)].`
  line `3 [ 33. Officers and employees etc., to be public servant. — The Adjudicating Authority, Competent`
  line `Authority and the Special Director (Appeals) and other officers and employees of the Special Director`
  line `(Appeals) shall be deemed to be public servants within the meaning of section 21 of the Indian Penal`
  line `Code, 1860 (45 of 1860).]`
  line `34. Civil court not to have jurisdiction. — No civil court shall have jurisdiction to entertain any suit`
  line `or proceeding in respect of any matter which an Adjudicating Authority or the Appellate Tribunal or the`
  line `Special Director (Appeals) is empowered by or under this Act to determine and no injunction shall be`
  line `granted by any court or other authority in respect of any action taken or to be taken in pursuance of any`
  line `power conferred by or under this Act.`
  line `35. Appeal to High Court. — Any person aggrieved by any decision or order of the Appellate`
  line `Tribunal may file an appeal to the High Court within sixty days from the date of communication of the`
  line `decision or order of the Appellate Tribunal to him on any question of law arising out of such order:`
  line `Provided that the High Court may, if it is satisfied that the appellant was prevented by sufficient cause`
  line `from filing the appeal within the said period, allow it to be filed within a further period not exceeding`
  line `sixty days.`
  line `Explanation. — In this section “ High Court ” means —`
  line `( a ) the High Court within the jurisdiction of which the aggrieved party ordinarily resides or`
  line `carries on business or personally works for gain; and`
  line `1. Subs by Act 7 of 2017, s. 165, for “Appellate Tribunal or the Special Director (Appeals” (w.e.f. 26 -5-2017).`
  line `2. Subs. by s. 165, ibid., for “Appellate Tribunal or the Special Director (Appeals), as the case may be” (w.e.f. 26 -5-2017).`
  line `3. Subs. by s. 165, ibid., for section 33 (w.e.f. 26-5-2017).`
obj_root_law_sections_15_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_16:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-16
  sectionNo (16)
  orderNo 16
  title `Page 16`
  content obj_root_law_sections_16_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_16_footnotes
  sourcePage 16
obj_root_law_sections_16_content:
  string
  line 16
  line `( b ) where the Central Government is the aggrieved party, the High Court within the jurisdiction`
  line `of which the respondent, or in a case where there are more than one respondent, any of the`
  line `respondents, ordinarily resides or carries on business or personally works for gain.`
  line `CHAPTER VI`
  line `D IRECTORATE OF E NFORCEMENT`
  line `36. Directorate of Enforcement. — ( 1 ) The Central Government shall establish a Directorate of`
  line `Enforcement with a Director and such other officers or class of officers as it thinks fit, who shall be called`
  line `officers of Enforcement, for the purposes of this Act.`
  line `( 2 ) Without prejudice to the provisions of sub-section ( 1 ), the Central Government may authorise the`
  line `Director of Enforcement or an Additional Director of Enforcement or a Special Director of Enforcement`
  line `or a Deputy Director of Enforcement to appoint officers of Enforcement below the rank of an Assistant`
  line `Director of Enforcement.`
  line `( 3 ) Subject to such conditions and limitations as the Central Government may impose, an officer of`
  line `Enforcement may exercise the powers and discharge the duties conferred or imposed on him under this`
  line Act.
  line `37. Power of search, seizure, etc. — ( 1 ) The Director of Enforcement and other officers of`
  line `Enforcement, not below the rank of an Assistant Director, shall take up for investigation the contravention`
  line `referred to in section 13.`
  line `( 2 ) Without prejudice to the provisions of sub-section ( 1 ), the Central Government may also, by`
  line `notification, authorise any officer or class of officers in the Central Government, State Government or the`
  line `Reserve Bank, not below the rank of an Under Secretary to the Government of India to investigate any`
  line `contravention referred to in section 13.`
  line `( 3 ) The officers referred to in sub-section ( 1 ) shall exercise the like powers which are conferred on`
  line `income-tax authorities under the Income-tax Act, 1961 (43 of 1961) and shall exercise such powers,`
  line `subject to such limitations laid down under that Act.`
  line `1 [37A. Special provisions relating to assets held outside India in contravention of`
  line `section 4. — ( 1 ) Upon receipt of any information or otherwise, if the Authorised Officer prescribed by the`
  line `Central Government has reason to believe that any foreign exchange, foreign security, or any immovable`
  line `property, situated outside India, is suspected to have been held in contravention of section 4, he may after`
  line `recording the reasons in writing, by an order, seize value equivalent, situated within Ind ia, of such foreign`
  line `exchange, foreign security or immovable property:`
  line `Provided that no such seizure shall be made in case where the aggregate value of such foreign`
  line `exchange, foreign security or any immovable property, situated outside India, is less than t he value as`
  line `may be prescribed.`
  line `( 2 ) The order of seizure along with relevant material shall be placed before the Competent Authority,`
  line `appointed by the Central Government, who shall be an officer not below the rank of Joint Secretary to the`
  line `Government of Ind ia by the Authorised Officer within a period of thirty days from the date of such`
  line seizure.
  line `( 3 ) The Competent Authority shall dispose of the petition within a period of one hundred eighty days`
  line `from the date of seizure by either confirming or by setting asid e such order, after giving an opportunity of`
  line `being heard to the representatives of the Directorate of Enforcement and the aggrieved person.`
  line `Explanation. — While computing the period of one hundred eighty days, the period of stay granted by`
  line `court shall be exc luded and a further period of at least thirty days shall be granted from the date of`
  line `communication of vacation of such stay order.`
  line `( 4 ) The order of the Competent Authority confirming seizure of equivalent asset shall continue till the`
  line `disposal of adjudicat ion proceedings and thereafter, the Adjudicating Authority shall pass appropriate`
  line `directions in the adjudication order with regard to further action as regards the seizure made under`
  line `sub - section ( 1 ):`
  line `1. Ins. by Act 20 of 2015, s. 142 (w.e.f. 9-9-2015).`
obj_root_law_sections_16_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_17:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-17
  sectionNo (17)
  orderNo 17
  title `Page 17`
  content obj_root_law_sections_17_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_17_footnotes
  sourcePage 17
obj_root_law_sections_17_content:
  string
  line 17
  line `Provided that if, at any stage of the pro ceedings under this Act, the aggrieved person discloses the`
  line `fact of such foreign exchange, foreign security or immovable property and brings back the same into`
  line `India, then the Competent Authority or the Adjudicating Authority, as the case may be, on receip t of an`
  line `application in this regard from the aggrieved person, and after affording an opportunity of being heard to`
  line `the aggrieved person and representatives of the Directorate of Enforcement, shall pass an appropriate`
  line `order as it deems fit, including settin g aside of the seizure made under sub - section ( 1 ).`
  line `( 5 ) Any person aggrieved by any order passed by the Competent Authority may prefer an appeal to`
  line `the Appellate Tribunal.`
  line `( 6 ) Nothing contained in section 15 shall apply to this section.]`
  line `38. Empowering other officers. — ( 1 ) The Central Government may, by order and subject to such`
  line `conditions and limitations as it thinks fit to impose, authorise any officer of customs or any central excise`
  line `officer or any police officer or any other officer of the Central Government or a State Government to`
  line `exercise such of the powers and discharge such of the duties of the Director of Enforcement or any other`
  line `officer of Enforcement under this Act as may be stated in the order.`
  line `( 2 ) The officers referred to in sub-section ( 1 ) shall exercise the like powers which are conferred on`
  line `the income-tax authorities under the Income-tax Act, 1961 (43 of 1961), subject to such conditions and`
  line `limitations as the Central Government may impose.`
  line `CHAPTER VII`
  line `M ISCELLANEOUS`
  line `39. Presumption as to documents in certain cases. — Where any document —`
  line `( i ) is produced or furnished by any person or has been seized from the custody or control of any`
  line `person, in either case, under this Act or under any other law; or`
  line `( ii ) has been received from any place outside India (duly authenticated by such authority or`
  line `person and in such manner as may be prescribed) in the course of investigation of any contravention`
  line `under this Act alleged to have been committed by any person,`
  line `and such document is tendered in any proceeding under this Act in evidence against him, or against him`
  line `and any other person who is proceeded against jointly with him, the court or the Adjudicating Authority,`
  line `as the case may be, shall —`
  line `( a ) presume, unless the contrary is proved, that the signature and every other part of such`
  line `document which purports to be in the handwriting of any particular person or which the court may`
  line `reasonably assume to have been signed by, or to be in the handwriting of, any particular person, is in`
  line `that person’ s handwriting, and in the case of a document executed or attested, that it was executed or`
  line `attested by the person by whom it purports to have been so executed or attested;`
  line `( b ) admit the document in evidence notwithstanding that it is not duly stamped, if such document`
  line `is otherwise admissible in evidence;`
  line `( c ) in a case falling under clause ( i ), also presume, unless the contrary is proved, the truth of the`
  line `contents of such document.`
  line `40. Suspension of operation of this Act. — ( 1 ) If the Central Government is satisfied that`
  line `circumstances have arisen rendering it necessary that any permission granted or restriction imposed by`
  line `this Act should cease to be granted or imposed, or if it considers necessary or expedient so to do in public`
  line `interest, the Central Government may, by notification, suspend or relax to such extent either indefinitely`
  line `or for such period as may be notified, the operation of all or any of the provisions of this Act.`
  line `( 2 ) Where the operation of any provision of this Act has under sub-section ( 1 ) been suspended or`
  line `relaxed indefinitely, such suspension or relaxation may, at any time while this Act remains in force, be`
  line `removed by the Central Government by notification.`
  line `( 3 ) Every notification issued under this section shall be laid, as soon as may be after it is issued,`
  line `before each House of Parliament, while it is in session, for a total period of thirty days which may be`
  line `comprised in one session or in two or more successive sessions, and if, before the expiry of the session`
obj_root_law_sections_17_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_18:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-18
  sectionNo (18)
  orderNo 18
  title `Page 18`
  content obj_root_law_sections_18_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_18_footnotes
  sourcePage 18
obj_root_law_sections_18_content:
  string
  line 18
  line `immediately following the session or the successive sessions aforesaid, both Houses agree in making any`
  line `modification in the notification or both Houses agree that the notification should not be issued, the`
  line `notification shall thereafter have effect only in such modified form or be of no effect, as the case may be;`
  line `so, however, that any such modification or annulment shall be without prejudice to the validity of`
  line `anything previously done under that notification.`
  line `41. Power of Central Government to give directions. — For the purposes of this Act, the Central`
  line `Government may, from time to time, give to the Reserve Bank such general or special directions as it`
  line `thinks fit, and the Reserve Bank shall, in the discharge of its functions under this Act, comply with any`
  line `such directions.`
  line `42. Contravention by companies. — ( 1 ) Where a person committing a contravention of any of the`
  line `provisions of this Act or of any rule, direction or order made thereunder is a company, every person who,`
  line `at the time the contravention was committed, was in charge of, and was responsible to, the company for`
  line `the conduct of the business of the company as well as the company, shall be deemed to be guilty of the`
  line `contravention and shall be liable to be proceeded against and punished accordingly:`
  line `Provided that nothing contained in this sub-section shall render any such person liable to punishment`
  line `if he proves that the contravention took place without his knowledge or that he exercised due diligence to`
  line `prevent such contravention.`
  line `( 2 ) Notwithstanding anything contained in sub-section ( 1 ), where a contravention of any of the`
  line `provisions of this Act or of any rule, direction or order made thereunder has been committed by a`
  line `company and it is proved that the contravention has taken place with the consent or connivance of, or is`
  line `attributable to any neglect on the part of, any director, manager, secretary or other officer of the company,`
  line `such director, manager, secretary or other officer shall also be deemed to be guilty of the contravention`
  line `and shall be liable to be proceeded against and punished accordingly.`
  line `Explanation. — For the purposes of this section —`
  line `( i ) “ company ” means any body corporate and includes a firm or other association of individuals;`
  line and
  line `( ii ) “ director ”, in relation to a firm, means a partner in the firm.`
  line `43. Death or insolvency in certain cases. — Any right, obligation, liability, proceeding or appeal`
  line `arising in relation to the provisions of section 13 shall not abate by reason of death or insolvency of the`
  line `person liable under that section and upon such death or insolvency such rights and obligations shall`
  line `devolve on the legal representative of such person or the official receiver or the official assignee, as the`
  line `case may be:`
  line `Provided that a legal representative of the deceased shall be liable only to the extent of the inheritance`
  line `or estate of the deceased.`
  line `44. Bar of legal proceedings. — No suit, prosecution or other legal proceeding shall lie against the`
  line `Central Government or the Reserve Bank or any officer of that Government or of the Reserve Bank or`
  line `any other person exercising any power or discharging any functions or performing any duties under this`
  line `Act, for anything in good faith done or intended to be done under this Act or any rule, regulation,`
  line `notification, direction or order made thereunder.`
  line `1 [ 44A. Powers of Reserve Bank not to apply to International Financial Services Centre. —`
  line `Notwithstanding anything contained in any other law for the time being in force, the powers exercisable`
  line `by the Reserve Bank under this Act, —`
  line `( a ) shall not extend to an International Financial Services Centre set up under sub-section (1) of`
  line `section 18 of the Special Economic Zones Act, 2005 (28 of 2005);`
  line `( b ) shall be exercisable by the International Financial Services Centres Authority established`
  line `under sub-section (1) of section 4 of the International Financial Services Centres Authority Act, 2019,`
  line `in so far as regulation of financial products, financial services and financial institutions that are`
  line `permitted in the International Financial Services Centres are concerned.]`
  line `1. Ins. by Act 50 of 2019, s. 33 and the second Schedule (w.e.f. 1-10-2020).`
obj_root_law_sections_18_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_19:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-19
  sectionNo (19)
  orderNo 19
  title `Page 19`
  content obj_root_law_sections_19_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_19_footnotes
  sourcePage 19
obj_root_law_sections_19_content:
  string
  line 19
  line `45. Removal of difficulties. — ( 1 ) If any difficulty arises in giving effect to the provisions of this Act,`
  line `the Central Government may, by order, do anything not inconsistent with the provisions of this Act for`
  line `the purpose of removing the difficulty:`
  line `Provided that no such order shall be made under this section after the expiry of two years from the`
  line `commencement of this Act.`
  line `( 2 ) Every order made under this section shall be laid, as soon as may be after it is made, before each`
  line `House of Parliament.`
  line `46. Power to make rules. — ( 1 ) The Central Government may, by notification, make rules to carry`
  line `out the provisions of this Act.`
  line `( 2 ) Without prejudice to the generality of the foregoing power, such rules may provide for, —`
  line `( a ) the imposition of reasonable restrictions on current account transactions under section 5;`
  line `1 [ ( aa ) the instruments which are determined to be debt instruments under sub - section ( 7 ) of`
  line `section 6;`
  line `( ab ) the permissible classes of capital account transactions in accordance with`
  line `sub - section ( 2A ) of section 6, the limits of admissibility of foreign exchange, and the prohibition,`
  line `restriction or regulation of such transactions; ]`
  line `( b ) the manner in which the contravention may be compounded under sub-section ( 1 ) of`
  line `section 15;`
  line `( c ) the manner of holding an inquiry by the Adjudicating Authority under sub-section ( 1 ) of`
  line `section 16;`
  line `( d ) the form of appeal and fee for filing such appeal under sections 17 and 19;`
  line `( e ) the salary and allowances payable to and the other terms and conditions of service of the`
  line `2 [Special Director (Appeals)] under section 23;`
  line `( f ) the salaries and allowances and other conditions of service of the officers and employees of the`
  line `3 [office of the Special Director (Appeals)] under sub-section ( 3 ) of section 27;`
  line `( g ) the additional matters in respect of which the Appellate Tribunal and the Special Director`
  line `(Appeals) may exercise the powers of a civil court under clause ( i ) of sub-section ( 2 ) of section 28;`
  line `4 [( gg ) the aggregate value of foreign exchange referred to in sub - section ( 1 ) of section 37A;]`
  line `( h ) the authority or person and the manner in which any document may be authenticated under`
  line `clause ( ii ) of section 39; and`
  line `( i ) any other matter which is required to be, or may be, prescribed.`
  line `47. Power to make regulations. — ( 1 ) The Reserve Bank may, by notification, make regulations to`
  line `carry out the provisions of this Act and the rules made thereunder.`
  line `( 2 ) Without prejudice to the generality of the foregoing power, such regulations may provide for, —`
  line `5 [ ( a ) the permissible classes of capital account transactions involving debt instruments`
  line `determined under sub - section ( 7 ) of section 6, the limits of admissibility of foreign exchange for such`
  line `transactions, and the prohibition, restriction or regulation of such capital account transactions under`
  line `section 6; ]`
  line `( b ) the manner and the form in which the declaration is to be furnished under clause ( a ) of`
  line `sub-section ( 1 ) of section 7;`
  line `1. Ins. by Act 20 of 2015, s. 143 (w.e.f. 15-10-2019).`
  line `2. Subs. by Act 7 of 2017, s. 165, for “Chairperson and other Member of the Appellate Tribunal and the Special Director`
  line `(Appeals) (w.e.f. 26-5-2017).`
  line `3. Subs. by s. 165, ibid., for “Appellate Tribunal and the office of the Special Director (Appeals)” (w.e.f. 26-5-2017).`
  line `4. Ins. by Act 20 of 2015, s. 143 (w.e.f. 15-10-2019).`
  line `5. Subs. by s. 144, ibid., for clause ( a ) (w.e.f. 15-10-2019).`
obj_root_law_sections_19_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_20:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-20
  sectionNo (20)
  orderNo 20
  title `Page 20`
  content obj_root_law_sections_20_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_20_footnotes
  sourcePage 20
obj_root_law_sections_20_content:
  string
  line 20
  line `( c ) the period within which and the manner of repatriation of foreign exchange under section 8;`
  line `( d ) the limit up to which any person may possess foreign currency or foreign coins under`
  line `clause ( a ) of section 9;`
  line `( e ) the class of persons and the limit up to which foreign currency account may be held or`
  line `operated under clause ( b ) of section 9;`
  line `( f ) the limit up to which foreign exchange acquired may be exempted under clause ( d ) of`
  line `section 9;`
  line `( g ) the limit up to which foreign exchange acquired may be retained under clause ( e ) of section 9;`
  line `1 [( g a ) export, import or holding of currency or currency notes;]`
  line `( h ) any other matter which is required to be, or may be, specified.`
  line `2 [( 3 ) All regulations made by the Reserve Bank before the date on which the provisions of this section`
  line `are notified under section 6 and section 47 of this Act on capital account transactions, the regulation`
  line `making power in respect of which now vests with the Central Government, shall continue to be valid,`
  line `until amended or res c inded by the Central Government.]`
  line `48. Rules and regulations to be laid before Parliament. — Every rule and regulation made under this`
  line `Act shall be laid, as soon as may be after it is made, before each House of Parliament, while it is in`
  line `session for a total period of thirty days which may be comprised in one session or in two or more`
  line `successive sessions, and if, before the expiry of the session immediately following the session or the`
  line `successive sessions aforesaid, both Houses agree in making any modification in the rule or regulation, or`
  line `both Houses agree that the rule or regulation should not be made, the rule or regulation shall thereafter`
  line `have effect only in such modified form or be of no effect, as the case may be; so, however, that any such`
  line `modification or annulment shall be without prejudice to the validity of anything previously done under`
  line `that rule or regulation.`
  line `49. Repeal and saving. — ( 1 ) The Foreign Exchange Regulation Act, 1973 (46 of 1973) is hereby`
  line `repealed and the Appellate Board constituted under sub-section ( 1 ) of section 52 of the said Act`
  line `(hereinafter referred to as the repealed Act) shall stand dissolved.`
  line `( 2 ) On the dissolution of the said Appellate Board, the person appointed as Chairman of the Appellate`
  line `Board and every other person appointed as Member and holding office as such immediately before such`
  line `date shall vacate their respective offices and no such Chairman or other person shall be entitled to claim`
  line `any compensation for the premature termination of the term of his office or of any contract of service.`
  line `( 3 ) Notwithstanding anything contained in any other law for the time being in force, no court shall take`
  line `cognizance of an offence under the repealed Act and no adjudicating officer shall take notice of any`
  line `contravention under section 51 of the repealed Act after the expiry of a period of two years from the date`
  line `of the commencement of this Act.`
  line `( 4 ) Subject to the provisions of sub-section ( 3 ) all offences committed under the repealed Act shall`
  line `continue to be governed by the provisions of the repealed Act as if that Act had not been repealed.`
  line `( 5) Notwithstanding such repeal, —`
  line `( a ) anything done or any action taken or purported to have been done or taken including any rule,`
  line `notification, inspection, order or notice made or issued or any appointment, confirmation or`
  line `declaration made or any license, permission, authorization or exemption granted or any document or`
  line `instrument executed or any direction given under the Act hereby repealed shall, in so far as it is not`
  line `inconsistent with the provisions of this Act, be deemed to have been done or taken under the`
  line `corresponding provisions of this Act;`
  line `( b ) any appeal preferred to the Appellate Board under sub-section ( 2 ) of section 52 of the`
  line `repealed Act but not disposed of before the commencement of this Act shall stand transferred to and`
  line `shall disposed of by the Appellate Tribunal constituted under this Act;`
  line `1. Ins. by Act 20 of 2015, s. 144 (w.e.f. 15-10-2019).`
  line `2. Ins. by s. 144. ibid. (w.e.f. 15-10-2019).`
obj_root_law_sections_20_footnotes:
  string
  line
